Prompt

You are the founder of a successful AI startup and have hired many AI engineers.
I am a B.Tech Computer Science student currently learning Python, Java, DSA, and AI. I want to become an AI Engineer and secure a good internship within the next year.
Guide me from a founder's perspective. Explain:
- Which skills matter the most
- What projects I should build
- How to create an impressive portfolio
- How to stand out from other students
- How to network effectively
- Common mistakes students make
- A practical 12-month roadmap     


🎯 What Skills Actually Matter (From Someone Who Reviews Resumes)
The brutal truth: 90% of applicants list the same skills. What separates the 10% I actually call?
Tier 1 — Non-Negotiable

Python (deeply) — not just syntax. I mean clean code, OOP, decorators, async, error handling. I can tell in 5 minutes of reading your code if you really know Python.
LLM APIs — OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini. Know how to call them, chain them, handle failures, manage cost.
RAG Systems — every AI product we've built uses this. If you can build a solid RAG pipeline, you're already ahead of 80% of applicants.
Git discipline — meaningful commit messages, branching, PRs. Sloppy Git = sloppy engineer.

Tier 2 — Strong Differentiators

Prompt Engineering — underrated. The engineer who writes better prompts ships better products.
FastAPI / Flask — wrap your models in an API. AI that can't be consumed is useless.
Docker basics — if I can't run your project in 2 commands, I probably won't.
Vector DBs — Pinecone, ChromaDB. Know why they exist, not just how to use them.

Tier 3 — Nice to Have

Basic ML/Deep Learning theory (Scikit-learn, PyTorch)
Cloud deployment (AWS/GCP free tier is enough to learn)
SQL — you'll always need it


What I don't care about: Your CGPA (unless it's terrible), certificates from random platforms, "proficiency in C++" listed at the top of your resume, or 10 skills listed that you clearly Googled.


🏗️ Projects You Should Build (The Ones That Actually Impress Me)
Rule: Don't build what tutorials tell you to. Build what solves a real problem.
Project 1 — A RAG-Powered Document Assistant (Months 3–5)

Upload PDFs → chunk → embed → store in vector DB → query with LLM
Add a clean UI (Streamlit is fine)
What makes it impressive: Evaluate it. Show retrieval accuracy. Show where it fails. That shows engineering maturity.

Project 2 — An AI Agent with Tool Use (Months 5–7)

An agent that can search the web, read files, call APIs, and complete multi-step tasks
Use LangChain or build your own lightweight version
What makes it impressive: Show it handling edge cases and failures gracefully

Project 3 — A Deployed AI Product (not a demo) (Months 7–9)

Something with a real URL that real users can access
Can be small — an AI email summarizer, a resume reviewer, a coding assistant
What makes it impressive: It's live. Most students never deploy. This alone sets you apart.

Project 4 — Your "Flagship" (Months 9–11)

Something you genuinely care about
For Indian students: EdTech AI tutor, vernacular language tools, agriculture AI, healthcare Q&A
What makes it impressive: Domain insight + AI skills = rare combination


My personal rule when reviewing portfolios: If I can replicate your project by following a YouTube tutorial in 2 hours, it's not impressive. Show me your thinking, not just your output.


📁 How to Build a Portfolio That Makes Me Stop Scrolling
Most student portfolios are graveyards of half-finished projects. Here's what a great one looks like:
GitHub Profile:

Pinned repos only for your best 4–6 projects
Every README must have: What it does, Why you built it, Architecture diagram, How to run it, What you learned / what failed
Consistent green activity — I look at contribution graphs

Personal Website (non-negotiable after Month 6):

One page is enough. Free with GitHub Pages or Vercel.
Your story, your projects with live links, your contact
A blog (even 3–4 posts) where you write about something you built or learned = instant credibility

LinkedIn:

Project posts with screenshots and a 3-line explanation of what you built
Engage with AI researchers and founders — not just "Great post!" but actual thoughts
"Open to internships" turned on


The portfolio test I use: I should be able to understand who you are, what you can do, and what you care about — in under 3 minutes. If I'm confused, you've lost me.


⚡ How to Stand Out (What 99% of Students Don't Do)
1. Write publicly. Start a newsletter or blog. "I built a RAG system and here's what broke" gets more attention than any certificate. Founders and engineers share good technical content.
2. Contribute to open source. Even small PRs to LangChain, Hugging Face, or any AI repo. It signals real-world collaboration skills and shows up on your GitHub.
3. Build in public on LinkedIn/Twitter. Post your progress weekly. "Day 30 of learning AI engineering — built my first RAG pipeline, here's what I learned." I've hired people I discovered this way.
4. Reach out cold — the right way. Not "Sir please give me internship." But: "I built a [specific thing] and ran into [specific problem]. I read your blog post on [specific topic] and tried your approach — here's what happened." I respond to those.
5. Niche down. "AI Engineer" is broad. "AI engineer focused on EdTech applications for vernacular languages" is memorable. Founders remember niches.

🤝 How to Network (That Doesn't Feel Gross)
The mindset shift: Networking isn't asking for favors. It's showing up where smart people are and contributing value.
Where to actually find people:

Twitter/X — most AI researchers and founders are very active here
Discord communities — Hugging Face, LangChain, AI Engineer Discord
Local meetups — search for AI/ML meetups in Delhi NCR (near Meerut) on Meetup.com
Hackathons — you meet founders, engineers, and potential co-founders in person

How to message someone:
