❌ Common Mistakes I See Students Make (That Kill Their Chances)
1. Tutorial hell. Watching 40 hours of courses and building zero projects. I cannot hire your YouTube watch history.
2. Listing skills you can't back up. "Proficient in TensorFlow, PyTorch, Keras, Scikit-learn, OpenCV, NLP, Computer Vision..." If I ask you to write a custom training loop live, can you? Be honest.
3. No README, no deployment, no documentation. A GitHub repo with just code files tells me you don't think about users — or reviewers.
4. Waiting until they're "ready" to apply. You'll never feel ready. Apply at Month 9 even if you feel like you're at 70%. The interview process itself teaches you.
5. Ignoring DSA. I've seen brilliant AI builders get rejected because they couldn't reverse a linked list. It's unfair but it's reality. Keep solving LeetCode in parallel — 3 problems a week minimum.
6. Building clones. "I built a ChatGPT clone" is the most common project I see. Build with AI, not a copy of it.
7. Zero online presence. If I Google your name and find nothing, you're at a disadvantage against someone with a visible portfolio.

📅 Your Practical 12-Month Roadmap
MONTH 1–2: FOUNDATION
├── Python: OOP, file handling, APIs, error handling
├── Math: Linear algebra + probability (3Blue1Brown on YouTube)
├── DSA: Arrays, strings, hashmaps, recursion (LeetCode Easy)
├── Git: Learn branching, commits, pull requests
└── Goal: Push 2 clean practice repos to GitHub

MONTH 3–4: ML + LLM BASICS
├── ML: Scikit-learn, regression, classification, evaluation
├── Deep Learning: Neural nets, PyTorch basics
├── LLM APIs: OpenAI/Anthropic API calls, prompt engineering
├── Build: Project 1 — RAG document assistant
└── Goal: First deployed project on Streamlit Cloud

MONTH 5–6: AI SYSTEMS
├── LangChain / LlamaIndex
├── Vector databases (ChromaDB / Pinecone)
├── FastAPI — wrap your AI in an API
├── Build: Project 2 — AI Agent with tool use
└── Goal: Personal website live, LinkedIn active

MONTH 7–8: PRODUCTION SKILLS
├── Docker — containerize your projects
├── Cloud basics — AWS/GCP free tier
├── Build: Project 3 — Deployed live AI product
├── Open source: First PR to any AI repo
└── Goal: 3 projects live with real URLs

MONTH 9–10: SPECIALIZATION + FLAGSHIP
├── Pick your domain (EdTech, Healthcare, FinTech)
├── Build: Project 4 — Flagship project with real users
├── Fine-tuning basics (Hugging Face)
├── DSA: LeetCode Medium (aim for 100+ solved)
└── Goal: Flagship project gets real users or attention

MONTH 11–12: INTERNSHIP SPRINT
├── Resume polish — 1 page, project-first format
├── Apply aggressively — startups, product companies, big tech
├── Mock interviews — DSA + AI concepts + system design
├── Cold outreach — 5 targeted messages/week
└── Goal: Internship offer in hand

💬 My Parting Advice as a Founder
When I hired my first AI engineers, I didn't hire the ones with the best grades or the most certificates. I hired the ones who could show me something they built, explain why they made certain decisions, and tell me honestly what went wrong and how they fixed it.
That's engineering. Build things. Break things. Write about it. Show up consistently for 12 months — and the internship will find you.
You're starting with Python, Java, DSA, and AI curiosity. That's a better starting point than most. Now go build something.
